Uninspired, moderately entertaining found footage film that is little more than a south of the equator knock off of the original "The Blair Witch Project." The story, acting, dialogue, camerawork, directing and all the rest are about average for a low budget horror film. The "shocking" conspiracy theory twist is lame, unless you're 12 or high or both. Far from the worst found footage movie movie I've seen, yet I still gotta say, keep your expectations low or you're likely to be disappointed. Definitely not the underappreciated sleeper we all hope to find on these streaming movie sites, but watchable.

The production starts off with the end found footage of a green ground cam and then works it way up to it. A group of people are follow migrating frogs in the Amazon Rainforest because they have evidence it produces an enzyme that can cure cancer. They listen to local folklore about the devil spirit Anhanga who protects locals from foreigners. One by one...

The creature...did we see a hand?...makes Predator noises. We are subject to the green cam, ground cam, Mina screaming in the dark cam, foot cam, jerk cam, and "what is that?" cam.

It was shot on location using real Brazilian customs, drink etc. The natives wore black Hanes under their loin cloths. The film gave us a false conspiracy message as the only new thing they added to found footage. Watch the Sean Connery version instead.

This film starts with a reasonable amount of promise and mystery.  The pace and plot are acceptable, the acting is reasonable. The conclusion in my opinion is juvenile to the point of childish and laughably absurd - overall, ruining the film for me.  If I had known where they were going with this, I would not have sat through the slow grind of the final 20 minutes.

This movie does not appear to be one of those shoestring-budget movies that so often dominate the found footage genre, so it really has no excuse for being as bad as it is. The twist at the end was pretty good but it is a long, long boring road leading up to it. The dittzy women on the team didn't help by their constant hysteria or their competence and grace while falling out of canoes or slipping into mud puddles, each time having to be rescued. The format was docu-drama rather than real "found-footage", which is a positive since the latter is usually an excuse for not bothering with quality camera-work or proper editing which was not the case here. Nevertheless, the creature's 50-millisecond appearance and a plot premise with a credibility of a Michael Moore docu-fantasy killed it.

This is nothing more than Blair Witch (but not as scary) in the jungle. Trying to lend itself credibility by using the premise of searching for a cancer cure doesn't work. While the acting is better than in some of the found-footage genre, the movie falls victim to the trappings of so many found-footage films...waiting too long for something to actually happen. Building suspense is one thing, but waiting too long leaves the audience like every potentially suspenseful moment will end in another disappointment. This movie would have been more effective if it showed us the "entity"/spirit part way through instead of leaving it to the final frames.

At first I think that I wouldn't like the movie, I'm not really partial to movies shot like a documentary. However, it was nicely filmed so after awhile I forgot it was shot that way! It was fairly predictable, but to be fair 99% of movies. Despite the predictability of the movie I actually enjoyed it fairly well.

This movie was awesome!  I especially enjoyed the found footage aspect, a very clever and original way to tell the story.  But, what really makes this film stand out is the sheer terror you feel while being stranded in the amazon jungle.  So spooky.  I feel like they could have charged $14.99 for this movie all day long and missed an opportunity by giving it away on Prime.  That's what's great about Prime, they always save the best movies for Prime members.  If you're still reading this, you may have already guessed that this review is pure sarcasm.  If I would have put 1 or 2 stars nobody would have really looked at this, I apologize for the bait and switch, but it was necessary.

35 minutes into the movie and "where's this movie going" ? Supposedly a legendary creature roams the jungle..a mythological creature called the "Anhanga" ... This film is one of those "hand held cams" all though the movie... most likely give you sea sickness instead of become fascinated with the story. I'll just skip this one and look for another film for viewing pleasure. This is not that. It probably would've been better if they filmed most of the scenery instead of three feet away from the actors/actresses.

And no I haven't been watching too many movies, it's what I believe. That beautiful jungle is being destroyed by progress.
